{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8400a761-f64f-49c0-a80f-6194229a3c85","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a dotnet tool:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <!-- Required: marks the project as a dotnet tool -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n\n  <!-- The command users will run (e.g., `dotnet tool install -g my-mcp-server`) -->\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- Must be Exe for a tool -->\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server using stdio transport.</Description>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n1. **`PackAsTool`** — the critical property that makes `dotnet pack` produce a tool package.\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command name after install.\n3. **`OutputType` must be `Exe`** — tools must be executable.\n\n**Publishing workflow:**\n\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push to NuGet.org (get your API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n**Users install with:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server   # runs via stdio\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"206b7854-63c3-4004-90c7-00480577ef04","outputTokens":469,"requestId":"C026:188512:1C99A9C:202FDC7:6A07C20B"},"id":"b4adfc2c-d75b-4bc3-8693-a8114aead47d","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:02:12.612Z","parentId":"8ceeee44-44f4-4cb2-882c-2d2695239fbc"}
